The sharing of a movement is like spreading an "epidemic" on the social network

This motivates us to develop a network epidemic model for the sharing data

Epidemic models

Compartment models

  • Susceptible-Infected-Recovered (SIR) model and its variants
  • Each individual is at exactly one stage at any time
  • Potentially goes from one stage to another

Classical assumptions governing the dynamics

  • Markovian
  • Homogeneous mixing

See e.g. Andersson and Britton (2000) (link)

Epidemic models

Modelling heterogeneity

Multiple levels of mixing

  • Ball, Mollison and Scalia-Tomba (1997): two levels
  • Britton, Kypraios and O’Neill (2011): three levels

Not quite applicable to our data

  • No information on such levels in the social network

Epidemic models

Network modelling

Bernoulli random graph (BRG)

  • Britton and O’Neill (2002) (link)
  • Neal and Roberts (2005) (link)

Both underlying network and transmission tree unknown

Focus on inference algorithms

BRG not quite realistic for social networks

Epidemic models

Network modelling

Identifiability issue

  • Inverse relationship between infection rate and edge inclusion probability
  • "Different explanations of the same outcome"
    (Britton and O’Neill, 2002)

Network models

Power-law degree distribution

Network models

Barabási and Albert (1999): Preferential attachment (PA) model

  • Each new node enters the network one by one, with \(\mu\) new edges
  • Each existing node gets an edge with probability proportional to current degree


image source

Network models

Small path lengths

  • Six degrees of separation

High clustering

  • Three typical nodes \(A,B\) and \(C\)
  • Assume \(A\leftrightarrow B\) and \(B\leftrightarrow C\)
  • Clustering coefficient: how likely that \(A\leftrightarrow C\)
  • BRG: whether each pair is connected is independent of other pairs a priori

Network models

Watts and Strogatz (1998): Small world model

  • Start with a "well-structured" network
    • lattice
  • Add random links or rewire the edges


image source

Network models

Epidemic modelling

Compartment models represented by ordinary differential equations (ODEs)

  • \(\displaystyle\frac{dS}{dt}=-\beta IS \qquad\qquad\frac{dI}{dt}=\beta IS-\gamma I \qquad\qquad\frac{dR}{dt}=\gamma I\)

Incorporate network aspects as covariate

  • E.g. same parameter values for individuals with same degree
  • Comprehensive review by Pastor-Satorras, Castellano, Van Mieghem and Vespignani (2015)

Quite remote from previously introduced statistical models

Ingredients

Population: \(m\) nodes/individuals

The epidemic times \(\boldsymbol{I}=(I_1,I_2,\ldots,I_m)\)

  • Susceptible-Infected (SI) model
  • Markovian, constant infection rate \(\beta\)

The underlying graph/network \(\boldsymbol{G}=\{G_{ij}\}_{m\times m}\)

  • Preferential attachment model, parameter \(\mu\)
  • \(G_{ij}=1\) if \(i\leftrightarrow j\) for \(i\neq j\), \(0\) otherwise

The transmission tree \(\boldsymbol{P}=\{P_{ij}\}_{m\times m}\)

  • \(P_{ij}=1\) if node \(j\) is infected by \(i\), \(0\) otherwise

Recipe

Step 1: Obtain new edges for the ordered nodes

Index the nodes by their order of entering the network

One edge to start with: nodes \(1\leftrightarrow2\)

Node \(i~(>2)\) brings in \(x_i\) new edges

  • \(x_i=\mu\) (constant) in original PA model too restrictive
  • \(x_i\sim\) truncated Poission \((\mu)\) (mean \(=\frac{\mu}{1-\exp(-\mu)}\))

Relationship between \(x_i\) and \(G_{ij}\)

\(x_i=\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}G_{ij}~\text{for}~i>2\)

Recipe

Step 1: Obtain new edges for the ordered nodes

\(\sum_{i=3}^{m}x_{i}+1=\sum\sum_{j<i}G_{ij}=\frac{1}{2}\sum\sum_{i\neq j}G_{ij}\)

\(\sum\text{(new edges)} + 1 = \text{total no. of edges} = \frac{1}{2}\sum\text{(individual degrees)}\)

Toy example: \(m=8,\mu=3\)

## [1,] . 1 1 1 1 1 1 .
## [2,] 1 . 1 1 1 1 . 1

## [4,] 1 1 . . . 1 . .

## [6,] 1 1 . 1 1 . . .
## [7,] 1 . . . 1 . . .
## [8,] . 1 . . . . . .

Recipe

Step 1: Obtain new edges for the ordered nodes

Likelihood: \[ L_1(\boldsymbol{G};\mu)=\prod_{i=3}^{m}\frac{e^{-\mu}\mu^{x_i}}{x_i!(1-e^{-\mu})}\\ \quad\quad\quad~~~=\frac{e^{-(m-2)\mu}\mu^{\sum\sum_{j<i}G_{ij}-1}}{(1-e^{-\mu})^{m-2}\prod_{i=3}^{m}(x_i!)} \]

Total number of edges sufficient for \(\mu\)

Recipe

Step 2: Construct the underlying network

When node \(i\) enters

  • \(x_i\) existing nodes chosen from \(\{1,2,\ldots,i-1\}\)
  • Weighted sampling without replacement
  • Weight of existing node \(j = \frac{\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}{\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}\)

Exact likelihood

  • Go through all \(x_i!\) permutations of the selected nodes
  • When \(x=1,2,3,4,5,6,7,\ldots,~x!=1,2,6,24,120,720,5040,\ldots\)
  • Computationally not feasible

Recipe

Step 2: Construct the underlying network

Approximation by likelihood under weighted sampling with replacement

Contribution by node \(i\)'s new edges: \[ L_{2i}=x_i!\times\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}} {\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}\right)^{G_{ij}} \]

Likelihood by the process of adding new edges: \[ L_2(\boldsymbol{G}):=\prod_{i=3}^{m}L_{2i}= \prod_{i=3}^{m}(x_i!)\times \prod_{i=3}^{m}\prod_{j=1}^{i-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}} {\sum_{j=1}^{i-1}\sum_{k=1}^{i-1}G_{kj}}\right)^{G_{ij}} \]

Recipe

Step 3: Spread the epidemic on the given network

Index the nodes by their epidemic (temporal) order

Infected node \(i\) makes infectious contacts

  • with its network neighbours
  • at points of Poisson process with rate \(\beta\sum_{j=1}^{m}G_{ij}\)

Likelihood independent of transmission tree \(\boldsymbol{P}\)

\(\pi(\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\beta)=\beta^{m-1}\exp\left(-\beta\sum\sum_{(i,j):G_{ij}=1}\left[(I_j-I_i)\vee0\right]\right)\\ \qquad\quad~=\beta^{m-1}\exp\left(-\beta\sum_{i=1}^{m}\sum_{j=i+1}^{m}G_{ij}(I_j-I_i)\right)\)

Recipe

Step 3: Spread the epidemic on the given network

So where is \(\boldsymbol{P}\) gone?

  • "Uniform distribution on the set of all possible infection pathways" (Britton and O’Neill, 2002)

\[ \pi(\boldsymbol{P}|\boldsymbol{G})\propto \prod_{j=2}^m \frac{1}{~\sum_{i=1}^{j-1}G_{ij}~} \times \prod_{i=1}^{m-1}\prod_{j=i+1}^{m}\mathbf{1}\left\{P_{ij}\leq G_{ij}\right\} \]

Posterior of \(\boldsymbol{G}\) involves \(\boldsymbol{P}\)

  • If \(P_{ij}=1\), \(G_{ij}=1\) with probability 1 (same for \(G_{ji}\)) a posteriori
  • More details in inference

Recipe

Step 4: Connect the network and the epidemic

Epidemic order not necessarily the same as network order

  • Fix the labelling of nodes by epidemic order
  • Introduce variable \(\boldsymbol{\sigma}\) - permutation of \(\{1,2,\ldots,m\}\)

Convert from epidemic order to network order

  • Replace \(\boldsymbol{G}\) by \(\boldsymbol{G}^{'}=f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma})\) when computing \(L_1(\cdot;\mu)\) and \(L_2(\cdot)\)

Recipe

Step 4: Connect the network and the epidemic

Toy example continued: \(m=8,\mu=3\)

  • \(\boldsymbol{\sigma}=(5,3,8,2,6,4,7,1)\)

Bayesian inference

\(\boldsymbol{G}\) is usually unknown

\(~~~~\pi(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu|\boldsymbol{P},\boldsymbol{I})\\ \propto\pi(\boldsymbol{P},\boldsymbol{I},\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\\ =\pi(\boldsymbol{P},\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\\ =\pi(\boldsymbol{P}|\boldsymbol{G})\times\pi(\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\beta)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{G}|\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma},\beta,\mu)\qquad(\boldsymbol{P}~\bot~\boldsymbol{I}~\text{given}~\boldsymbol{G})\\ =\pi(\boldsymbol{P}|\boldsymbol{G})\times\pi(\boldsymbol{I}|\boldsymbol{G},\beta)\times L_1\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu\right)L_2(\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma})\right)\times\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma})\pi(\beta)\pi(\mu)\)

Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm straightforward

  • Similar latent approach if \(\boldsymbol{P}\) is also unknown

Bayesian inference

Uninformative priors

\(\beta\sim\text{Gamma}(a_\beta, \text{rate}=b_\beta)\)

\(\mu\sim\text{Gamma}(a_\mu, \text{rate}=b_\mu)\)

\(\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma})=(m!)^{-1}\)

Bayesian inference

Posteriors

\(\beta|\ldots\sim \text{Gamma}\left(a_\beta+m-1,\text{rate}=b_\beta+\sum_{i=1}^{m}\sum_{j=i+1}^{m}G_{ij}(I_j-I_i)\right)\)

\(\pi(\mu|\ldots)\propto e^{-(b_{\mu}+m-2)\mu}\mu^{a_{\mu}+\sum\sum_{j<i}G_{ij}-2}(1-e^{-\mu})^{2-m}\boldsymbol{1}\{\mu>0\}\)

\(\pi(\boldsymbol{\sigma}|\ldots)\propto L_1\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu\right)L_2(\left(f(\boldsymbol{G},\boldsymbol{\sigma})\right)\)

Exploring permutation space

  • Bezáková, Kalai and Santhanam (2006): link
  • Random insertion
  • More efficient than random swap

Bayesian inference

Posteriors

\(\Pr(G_{ij}=1|P_{ij}=1,\ldots)=1\)

\(\boldsymbol{G}_0~(\boldsymbol{G}_1)\) the same as \(\boldsymbol{G}\) with \(G_{ij}\) and \(G_{ji}\) set to \(0 (1)\)

\(\Pr(G_{ij}=0|P_{ij}=0,\boldsymbol{G}_{-ij},\ldots)\propto \displaystyle\frac{L_1(f(\boldsymbol{G}_0,\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu)~L_2(f(\boldsymbol{G}_0,\boldsymbol{\sigma}))} {\sum_{k=1,k\neq i}^{j-1}G_{kj}}\)

\(\Pr(G_{ij}=1|P_{ij}=0,\boldsymbol{G}_{-ij},\ldots)\propto \displaystyle\frac{L_1(f(\boldsymbol{G}_1,\boldsymbol{\sigma});\mu)~L_2(f(\boldsymbol{G}_1,\boldsymbol{\sigma}))~e^{-\beta(I_j-I_i)}} {\sum_{k=1,k\neq i}^{j-1}G_{kj}+1}\)

Perfect?

  • Not quite

  • Problematic

Observations

Inverse relationship between epidemic rate \(\beta\) and parameter characterising network connectedness

  • Average number new edges \(\mu\) in PA model
  • Edge inclusion probability \(p\) in BRG model
    • Echoing observation by Britton and O’Neill (2002)

Under reparameterisation \(\alpha=\beta\mu\)

  • Identifying one parameter \((\alpha)\) as good as we can get
  • Mixing/convergence similar
  • Interpretation

Application - App Movement

Still waiting for results!

Typical times taken per iteration:

  • \(m=100: 0.88\text{s}\)
  • \(m=200: 14\text{s}\)

Computational time \(O(m^4)\)

  • # edges \((G_{ij})\) to update \(O(m^2)\)
  • # computations involved in updating one edge \(O(m^2)\)

Data sets worth applying the model to

  • \(m = 350\) and up

Summary

Review on network epidemics

  • Statistical models assume BRG, unrealistic
  • Physical models focus on dynamics, difficult to do inference

Model and inference

  • PA model to grow network, SI model to spread epidemic
  • MCMC algorithm: Gibbs steps for \(\beta\) and individual edges \(G_{ij}\), Metropolis steps for \(\mu\) and \(\boldsymbol{\sigma}\)

Simulation study

  • Product of \(\beta\) and \(\mu\) identifiable but not individually
